gs to the festival in order to explore deeper questions of identity formation and cultural appropriation. The book traces the growth of Latin American communities in Britain; the popularity of Latin American literature, music, and film in many of the country's largest cities, including London and Manchester; and shows how people in Britain who do not have Latin American origins consume Latin American culture to reconcile issues of self-identity and cosmopolitanism. Imagining Latin America presents a new and innovative approach to Latin American Studies and makes an important contribution to contemporary debates about the cultural integration of immigrant communities and transnational exchange.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 07. Mrz 2024) 0aCosmopolitanism. 0aCultural appropriationzGreat Britain. 0aImmigrants in motion pictures. 0aLatin Americans in motion pictures. 0aMagic in motion pictures. 0aMagic realism (Literature). 0aRealism in motion pictures. 4aFilm & Theatre. 4aHispanic Studies. 4aSocial History. 7aPERFORMING ARTS / Film & Video / History & Criticism.2bisacsh  aLatin American culture.  acultural integration.  aimmigrant communities.  amagical realism.  atransnational exchange.  a¡Viva! Film Festival.08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertBoydell and Brewer Complete eBook-Package 2021z978311143100040uhttps://www.degruyter.com/isbn/9781787445758423Coveruhttps://www.degruyter.com/document/cover/isbn/9781787445758/original  a978-3-11-143100-0  Boydell and Brewer Complete eBook-Package 2021b2021  aGBV-deGruyter-alles